verted into 12 special symbols + advanced 9 symbols. 

The word Lama means Disciple of lord Buddha and the word Fera means round or more specifically around the body with the energy of lord Buddha. The Energy of lord Buddha is channeled through the Healer and directed towards disease or illness. 

This system of Lama Fera heals through the release of blockages of the life force in the chakras. It helps in increasing spiritual abilities, relieve pain and discomfort caused by chronic disease, removes unwanted spirits, overcome fear, anxiety, stress and helps one connect with higher self. It is considered as the fastest healing technique for physic problems,It removes pressure of thoughts and increases the vital energy of the bodies. Though this method of healing is quite different from Reiki and other types of healing therapies, it can, like them, be used in distant healing.";s:6:"parent";s:4:"1391";s:5:"count";s:2:"14";s:9:"object_id";s:5:"15049";}i:35;O:8:"stdClass":10:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1407";s:4:"name";s:23:"Magnified Healing Phase";s:4:"slug";s:23:"magnified-healing-phase";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1407";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"therapy";s:11:"description";s:590:"Magnified Healing Phase is a holistic approach to healing the body naturally. The practitioner combines healing energy with voice and movement. It establishes a constant flow of energy from the heart to the Source, the All That Is, through all of the spiritual centers down to the diamond at the center of the Earth. The practitioner places one hand in front of the body and the other at the back of the client who is receiving the healing. The energy goes from one hand to the other through the body of the client leading to healing on the physical, emotional, mental and spiritual levels.";s:6:"parent";s:4:"1391";s:5:"count";s:1:"6";s:9:"object_id";s:5:"15049";}i:36;O:8:"stdClass":10:{s:7:"term_id";s:3:"722";s:4:"name";s:11:"Maharashtra";s:4:"slug";s:11:"maharashtra";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:3:"722";s:8:"taxonomy";s:8:"location";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:6:"parent";s:3:"721";s:5:"count";s:3:"616";s:9:"object_id";s:5:"11403";}i:37;O:8:"stdClass":10:{s:7:"term_id";s:3:"722";s:4:"name";s:11:"Maharashtra";s:4:"slug";s:11:"maharashtra";s:10:"term_group";